<div id="review_1403022100" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1403022100" />
    <a title="Cheryl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/165321-cheryl"><img alt="Cheryl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1236058978p2/165321.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1403022100?book_show_action=true">Sep 28, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cheryl" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cheryl" href="/user/show/165321-cheryl">Cheryl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1403022100" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15415318034721573105">Holy mackerel. Ok, this was a page turner, and I finished it in two days. Like many other readers, I found it to be riveting, and I simply couldn&apos;t put it down. <br/><br/>I really wanted to give this book a 4.5 star rating, as there were only two things keeping it from being 5 stars in my book. The first was the main character&apos;s tendency to berate herself for forgetting about her children all the time and then simply failing to do something to ensure this wouldn&apos;t happen. I wasn&apos;t sure if this was a repre</span>
  <span id="freeText15415318034721573105" style="display:none">Holy mackerel. Ok, this was a page turner, and I finished it in two days. Like many other readers, I found it to be riveting, and I simply couldn't put it down. <br /><br />I really wanted to give this book a 4.5 star rating, as there were only two things keeping it from being 5 stars in my book. The first was the main character's tendency to berate herself for forgetting about her children all the time and then simply failing to do something to ensure this wouldn't happen. I wasn't sure if this was a representation of how distracted she was because of the abuse, or just a character flaw, but I found it overdone. Second, she cites her gratitude to the people at Elmer Creek who take her in, feed her, give her a job, basically shelter her at their own risk - - - but once she is back in her old life, there is no mention of any of them. <br /><br />Still - - - I worked in Domestic Violence for years, and I found this story to be very realistic and true to life. I would HIGHLY recommend this to anyone who has never been able to understand why a woman "just can't leave". Well done, Ms. Redfearn!!!!</span>
  <a data-text-id="15415318034721573105" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


